THOUGHT: The `swfdump` command with the POC file resulted in a segmentation fault, as expected. The AddressSanitizer output points to `rfxswf.c:213` within the `swf_GetBits` function.

The `search_file_content` tool output shows `rfxswf.c:213` is part of a `for` loop within `swf_GetBits`:

```c
206-  while (nbits)
207-  { res<<=1;
208-#ifdef DEBUG_RFXSWF
209-    if (t->pos>=t->len) 
210-    { fprintf(stderr,"GetBits() out of bounds: TagID = %i, pos=%d, len=%d\n",t->id, t->pos, t->len);
211-      int i,m=t->len>10?10:t->len;
212-      for(i=-1;i<m;i++) {
213-        fprintf(stderr,"%02x ",(unsigned char)t->data[t->pos+i]);
214-      }
215-      fprintf(stderr,"\n");
216-      return 0;
217-    }
218-#endif
219-    if (t->data[t->pos] & t->readBit) res|=1;
220-    t->readBit>>=1;
```

The crash occurs at line 213: `fprintf(stderr,"%02x ",(unsigned char)t->data[t->pos+i]);`. This line is inside a `for` loop that iterates from `i = -1` to `m-1`. The value `m` is `t->len > 10 ? 10 : t->len`.

The problem is `t->pos+i` when `i` is `-1`. If `t->pos` is 0, then `t->pos+i` becomes `-1`, which is an out-of-bounds access for `t->data`. This is a classic buffer underflow.

This code is within a `DEBUG_RFXSWF` block, which means it's debug code. The `fprintf` is trying to print context around the `t->pos` when `t->pos >= t->len` (an out-of-bounds read). However, the debug code itself introduces an out-of-bounds read when `i` is negative.

To fix this, the loop for printing debug information should ensure that `t->pos+i` is always a valid index. The simplest fix is to start `i` from 0, or to ensure `t->pos+i` is non-negative. Since the intent is to print *context* around `t->pos`, printing `t->data[t->pos-1]` is valid if `t->pos > 0`.

However, the `if (t->pos>=t->len)` condition already indicates an error. The debug print should probably only print valid data. Printing `t->data[t->pos+i]` when `t->pos+i` can be negative is incorrect.

I will modify the loop to start `i` from 0, ensuring `t->pos+i` is always non-negative. This will prevent the underflow.

```bash
sed -i 's/for(i=-1;i<m;i++) {/for(i=0;i<m;i++) {/' lib/rfxswf.c
```

